In Java, you can add color to your console output by using ANSI escape codes. These codes provide a way to manipulate the text appearance in the terminal, including changing the text color. However, keep in mind that not all terminals support ANSI escape codes, so make sure the one you are using does.

To print colored logs, you can create a helper method that appends the appropriate ANSI escape codes to the log messages. Here&#39;s a simple example of how to do that:

    @Slf4j
    public class ColoredLogger {
    
        // ANSI escape codes for text colors
        private static final String ANSI_RESET = &quot;\u001B[0m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_BLACK = &quot;\u001B[30m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_RED = &quot;\u001B[31m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_GREEN = &quot;\u001B[32m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_YELLOW = &quot;\u001B[33m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_BLUE = &quot;\u001B[34m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_PURPLE = &quot;\u001B[35m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_CYAN = &quot;\u001B[36m&quot;;
        private static final String ANSI_WHITE = &quot;\u001B[37m&quot;;
    
        // Log levels
        public enum LogLevel {
            INFO(ANSI_GREEN),
            WARNING(ANSI_YELLOW),
            ERROR(ANSI_RED);
    
            private final String colorCode;
    
            LogLevel(String colorCode) {
                this.colorCode = colorCode;
            }
    
            public String getColorCode() {
                return colorCode;
            }
        }
    
        public static void log(LogLevel level, String message) {
                    log.info(level.getColorCode() + message + ANSI_RESET);

        }
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            log(LogLevel.INFO, &quot;This is an info message.&quot;);
            log(LogLevel.WARNING, &quot;This is a warning message.&quot;);
            log(LogLevel.ERROR, &quot;This is an error message.&quot;);
        }
    }

In this example, we have a ColoredLogger class with an inner LogLevel enum that represents different log levels. The log method takes a log level and a message as input, and it prints the message with the corresponding color to the console.

Remember that the appearance of the colored text depends on the terminal or console you are using. Some IDEs might not fully support ANSI escape codes, so the output may not show colors as intended. However, when running the code in a supported terminal, you should see the colored logs.

