answers.body_markdown:
It is called **(type) casting**.

From your description, I believe the `TrainEngine` class *extends* the `TrainCar` class and `getPower` method is present in the `TrainEngine` child class.

When you have a reference to a `TrainCar`, it could be any class which extends it. So by checking `car instanceof TrainEngine`, you are checking if the `TrainCar` reference is actually an instance of `TrainEngine` and if so you can **cast** the object which is stored as a `TrainCar` reference to a `TrainEngine`. 

```
if (car instanceof TrainEngine) {
    TrainEngine trainEngine = (TrainEngine) car;
}
```
Note: You aren&#39;t creating a new object here. You are just accessing the same object as a `TrainEngine` (the child class).

Now using the *trainEngine* local variable, you can access all the methods on the `TrainEngine` class and hence you can access the `getPower` method.

```
if (car instanceof TrainEngine) {
    TrainEngine trainEngine = (TrainEngine) car;
    totalPower += trainEngine.getPower();
}
```
The suggestion from IDE is to combine the cast and calling the `getPower` method in one line.
```
totalPower += ((TrainEngine) car).getPower();
```

